## Mr.Bin
The main idea finding the flag using Binwalk tool.

#### Step-1:
After we download `image.jpg` from the cloud, we see the following:

<img src="image.jpg">

#### Step-2:
We then use [binwalk](https://www.kali.org/tools/binwalk/) tool to extract two files from `image.jpg` - `bin` which was empty and `D0F0.zip`.

<img src="binwalk.png">

#### Step-3:
Then we unzip the `D0F0.zip` file where we are prompted for password. Luckily that can be found using the command `strings image.jpg | grep "pass"`. We come to know that the password is `mr_b1n`. I have fetched out the output of strings image.jpg to text file for quicker searching.

<img src="password.png">

#### Step-4:
Using the above password gives us a new `bin` file after unzipping it which shows `bin` file contains 360001 bytes. According to hint from `image.jpg`, `bin` is a `600x600` ASCII image. Using the command `strings image.jpg | head`, we get the following output

```bash
$ strings image.jpg | head
JFIF
NjAweDYwMF9waWN0dXJl
QA%C
(%-B
 B)X
k&v+
!`BB
%d @)
KBABXX0
L^W*Pd
```
The string `NjAweDYwMF9waWN0dXJl` if decrypted in Base64, we get it as `600x600_picture`.

#### Step-5:

The line was too long to read even reshaped it to matrix of `600x600`.  After trimming the  additional 0s from top, bottom, left and right, we get the below output. I have saved it in a file `600x600_picture`.
